<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1906-01-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1906-01-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="372" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d372">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Meyer</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">St.
                                        Petersburg</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-01-04"><hi rend="italic">January 4,
                                1906</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 391.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inclose, for the
                            information of the department, the French text<note n="a" xml:id="d372fna">Not printed.</note> of an imperial ukase dated the
                            14/27 of December, 1905, providing that in case of mutinies or strikes
                            on Russian railroads the managers of the lines may proclaim martial law
                            over all the property belonging to their division, and enacting measures
                            for enforcing this provision.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">G. von L. Meyer.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>